irror in Darkness (1934–1936) -- t19 David Jones, In Parenthesis (1937) -- t20 Rudyard Kipling, Poetry and Short Stories of the First World War -- t21 Vernon Lee, Satan the Waster (1920) and Peace with Honour (1915) -- t22 Rose Macaulay, Non-Combatants and Others (1916) and Other War Writings -- t23 Wilfred Owen, War Poetry -- t24 Ernest Raymond, Tell England (1922) and Other Writings -- t25 Isaac Rosenberg, War Poetry -- t26 Siegfried Sassoon, War Poems (1919) and The Complete Memoirs of George Sherston (1937) -- t27 R.C. Sherriff, Journey’s End (1928) -- t28 May Sinclair, A Journal of Impressions in Belgium (1915), War Poetry and Fiction -- t29 Virginia Woolf, Jacob’s Room (1922), Mrs. Dalloway (1925), To the Lighthouse (1927), The Years (1937) and Three Guineas (1938) -- t30 Joan Littlewood and the Theatre Workshop, Oh What a Lovely War (1963) -- t31 Susan Hill, Strange Meeting (1971) -- t32 Sebastian Faulks, Birdsong: A Novel of Love and War (1993) -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Names -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe First World War has given rise to a multifaceted cultural production like no other historical event. This handbook surveys British literature and film about the war from 1914 until today. The continuing interest in World War I highlights the interdependence of war experience, the imaginative re-creation of that experience in writing, and individual as well as collective memory. In the first part of the handbook, the major genres of war writing and film are addressed, including of course poetry and the novel, but also the short story; furthermore, it is shown how our conception of the Great War is broadened when looked at from the perspective of gender studies and post-colonial criticism. The chapters in the second part present close readings of important contributions to the literary and filmic representation of World War I in Great Britain. All in all, the contributions demonstrate how the opposing forces of focusing and canon-formation on the one hand, and broadening and revision of the canon on the other, have characterised British literature and culture of the First World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWar in literature. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xIn literature. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xLiterature and the war. 4a1. Weltkrieg. 4aEnglische Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBritish literature and film.  aWar Writing.  aWorld War I.1 aActon, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnerjee, Samraghni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriggs, Marlene A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDornhofer, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEinhaus, Ann-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmig, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrayn, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagel, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiovanelli, Marcello, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLancaster, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLöschnigg, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacdonald, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Jane , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPott